-- Asian Stocks Climb on Speculation Quantitative Easing Will Support Growth
-- B y   S h a n i   R a j a
-- 2010-11-05T10:01:59Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-11-05/asian-stocks-climb-on-speculation-quantitative-easing-will-support-growth.html
Asian  stocks  rose, driving the MSCI
Asia Pacific Index to its biggest weekly advance since December,
as Nissan Motor Co. boosted its profit forecast and commodity
prices climbed on speculation the U.S. Federal Reserve will
succeed in stoking economic growth.  Nissan , Japan’s third-biggest carmaker, jumped 6 percent in
Tokyo after also posting higher-than-expected earnings.  Canon
Inc. , which gets 27 percent of its sales in the Americas, gained
3.3 percent.  PetroChina Co. , Asia’s largest company by market
value, climbed 2.7 percent in Hong Kong.  BHP Billiton Ltd. , the
world’s No. 1 mining company, surged 3.6 percent in Sydney.  The  MSCI Asia Pacific Index  rose 1.4 percent to 135.23 as
of 7:00 p.m. in Tokyo, extending its gain this week to 4.5
percent. The gauge climbed 3.3 percent the past two days since
the Fed unveiled plans to buy an additional $600 billion of
Treasuries to bolster economic growth.  “We’re seeing follow-through strength in risky assets,
suggesting that not all of the U.S. quantitative-easing news was
in the price,” said  Prasad Patkar , who helps manage about $1.8
billion at Platypus Asset Management Ltd. in Sydney. “The
market had been expecting a second round of easing, but it
appears the rumor wasn’t bought to the extent feared. That’s why
we’re not seeing any selling.”  Japan’s Nikkei 225 Stock Average climbed 2.9 percent. Hong
Kong’s Hang Seng Index and China’s Shanghai Composite Index both
gained 1.2 percent. Malaysia and Singapore’s markets are shut
for public holidays. India’s stock market will open for a
truncated one-hour evening session to mark Diwali, the beginning
of the Hindu new year.  Bank of Japan  Australia’s S&P/ASX 200 Index rose 1.2 percent. The
country’s economic growth will accelerate next year, spurred by
trade and mining investment, while the local currency’s increase
to parity with the U.S. dollar will help slow  inflation , the
nation’s central bank said in a quarterly  report  today.  Futures on the  Standard & Poor’s 500 Index  lost 0.3 percent
as U.S. Treasury Secretary  Timothy F. Geithner  joined Asia-
Pacific Economic Cooperation forum counterparts for a two-day
meeting in Kyoto, Japan.  The S&P 500 jumped 1.9 percent yesterday, the most in a
month, as investors speculated the Fed will succeed in stoking
growth and that banks will raise dividends. The Bank of Japan is
scheduled to end a two-day meeting today. It advanced its review
of monetary policy to immediately follow the Fed.  Nissan Motor climbed 6 percent to 764 yen in Tokyo after
boosting its  forecast  for full-year net income by 80 percent.
Nomura Holdings Inc., Japan’s biggest brokerage, increased its
share-price estimate on the carmaker to 1,100 yen from 990 yen.  Toyota Motor Corp. , the world’s largest automaker, gained
1.9 percent to 2,964 yen.  Canon, Sony  About 130 companies of almost 1,000 in the MSCI Asia
Pacific Index were scheduled to announce earnings this week,
according to data compiled by Bloomberg. About six companies
have  exceeded profit estimates  for every five that have fallen
short, based on Bloomberg data compiled from about 440 companies
that have reported quarterly results since Oct. 7.  More than three stocks advanced in the MSCI gauge for each
one that fell. Canon climbed 3.3 percent to 3,905 yen in Tokyo.
Electronics maker Sony Corp., which derives more than 20 percent
of its sales in the U.S., gained 2.7 percent to 2,711 yen.  “With speculation of continuing excess liquidity, money is
flowing into risk assets” including stocks and commodities,
said  Hiroichi Nishi , an equities manager in Tokyo at Nikko
Cordial Securities Inc. “Uncertainties about the global
economic outlook are clearing.”  Positive Impact  The Fed’s plan is expected to have a “modest” positive
impact on the economy,  Caroline Atkinson , the International
Monetary Fund’s director of external relations, told reporters
in Washington yesterday.  The  MSCI Asia Pacific Index  increased 11 percent this year
to yesterday, compared with gains of 9.5 percent by the S&P 500
and 6.7 percent by the  Stoxx Europe 600 Index . Stocks in the
Asian benchmark are valued at 14.6 times estimated  earnings  on
average, compared with 14.4 times for the S&P 500 and 12.4 times
for the Stoxx 600.  A gauge of raw-material companies in the MSCI Asia Pacific
Index climbed 2.5 percent as the Fed’s plans to buy more U.S.
debt drove the dollar lower, boosting demand for commodities as
alternative investments.  Crude oil for December delivery rose 2.1 percent in New
York yesterday to the highest settlement price since April 6.
Copper futures advanced 3.3 percent to a 28-month high. Gold
futures surged to a record. The London Metal Exchange Index of
prices for six industrial metals including copper and aluminum
jumped 3.1 percent yesterday, the most since May.  Commodity Producers  PetroChina climbed 2.7 percent to HK$10.24 in Hong Kong.
Mitsubishi Corp., Japan’s largest commodities trader, gained 3
percent to 2,086 yen in Tokyo and  Korea Zinc Co. , the world’s
second-biggest zinc smelter, added 2.1 percent to 318,000 won in
Seoul. BHP Billiton rose 3.6 percent to A$45.27 in Sydney, while
Rio Tinto Group, the world’s No. 3 mining company, jumped 4.8
percent to A$87.20.  Caltex Australia Ltd. , the nation’s largest oil refiner,
surged 6 percent to A$12.61 in Sydney after Morgan Stanley
analysts upgraded the stock to “overweight” from “equal-
weight.”  Among stocks that declined today, Hong Kong’s  Hang Lung
Properties Ltd.  plunged 6.4 percent to HK$37.70 after saying it
will sell 293.86 million shares at HK$37.48 each.  In Tokyo, Resona Holdings Inc. tumbled 16 percent to 512
yen, the biggest decline in the MSCI Asia Pacific Index. The
bank, Japan’s fourth largest, is preparing a public share offer
of several hundred billions of yen, according to two people with
knowledge of the matter.  To contact the reporters for this story:
